#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:3
msgid "Configuring Federation Sharing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:5
msgid ""
"Federated Cloud Sharing is now managed by the Federation app (9.0+), and "
"is now called Federation sharing. When you enable the Federation app you "
"can easily and securely link file shares between ownCloud servers, in "
"effect creating a cloud of ownClouds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:11
msgid "Sharing With ownCloud 8 and Older"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:13
msgid ""
"Direct Federation shares (:ref:`label-direct-share-link`) are not "
"supported in ownCloud 8 and older, so you must create Federation shares "
"with public links (:ref:`label-public-link-share`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:20
msgid "Creating a new Federation Share (9.0+ only)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:22
msgid ""
"Follow these steps to create a new Federation share between two ownCloud "
"9.0+ servers. This requires no action by the user on the remote server; "
"all it takes is a few steps on the originating server."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:26
msgid "Enable the Federation app."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:28
msgid ""
"Go to your ownCloud Admin page and scroll to the Sharing section. Verify "
"that **Allow users on this server to send shares to other servers** and "
"**Allow users on this server to receive shares from other servers** are "
"enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:33
msgid ""
"Now go to the Federation section. By default, **Add server automatically "
"once a federated share was created successfully** is checked. The "
"Federation app supports creating a list of trusted ownCloud servers, "
"which allows the trusted servers to exchange user directories and auto-"
"complete the names of external users when you create shares. If you do "
"not want this enabled, then un-check it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:42
msgid ""
"Now go to your Files page and select a folder to share. Click the share "
"icon, and then enter the username and URL of the user on the remote "
"ownCloud server. In this example, that is "
"``freda@https://example.com/owncloud``. When ownCloud verifies the link, "
"it displays it with the **(remote)** label. Click on this label to "
"establish the link."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:50
msgid ""
"When the link is successfully completed, you have a single share option, "
"and that is **can edit**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:55
msgid "You may disconnect the share at any time by clicking the trash can icon."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:58
msgid "Configuring Trusted ownCloud Servers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:60
msgid ""
"You may create a list of trusted ownCloud servers for Federation sharing."
" This allows your linked ownCloud servers to share user directories, and "
"to auto-fill user names in share dialogs. If **Add server automatically "
"once a federated share was created successfully** is enabled on your "
"Admin page, servers will be automatically added to your trusted list when"
" you create new Federation shares."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:66
msgid ""
"You may also enter ownCloud server URLs in the **Add ownCloud Server** "
"field. The yellow light indicates a successful connection, with no user "
"names exchanged. The green light indicates a successful connection with "
"user names exchanged. A red light means the connection failed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:76
msgid "Creating Federation Shares via Public Link Share"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:78
msgid ""
"You'll need to use a Public Link Share to create Federation shares with "
"ownCloud 8.x and older."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:81
msgid ""
"Check the ``Share Link`` checkbox to expose more sharing options (which "
"are described more fully in :doc:`file_sharing_configuration`). You may "
"create a Federation share by allowing ownCloud to create a public link "
"for you, and then email it to the person you want to create the share "
"with."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:88
msgid ""
"You may optionally set a password and expiration date on it. When your "
"recipient receives your email they must click the link, or copy it to a "
"Web browser. They will see a page displaying a thumbnail of the file, "
"with a button to **Add to your ownCloud**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:95
msgid ""
"Your recipient should click the **Add to your ownCloud** button. On the "
"next screen your recipient needs to enter the URL to their ownCloud "
"server, and then press the return key."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:101
msgid ""
"Your recipient has to take one more step, and that is to confirm creating"
" the federated cloud share link by clicking the **Add remote share** "
"button."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:106
msgid ""
"Un-check the ``Share Link`` checkbox to disable any federated cloud share"
" created this way."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:110
msgid "Configuration Tips"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:112
msgid ""
"The Sharing section on your Admin page allows you to control how your "
"users manage federated cloud shares:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:115
msgid "Check ``Enforce password protection`` to require passwords on link shares."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:116
msgid ""
"Check ``Set default expiration date`` to require an expiration date on "
"link shares."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:118
msgid "Check ``Allow public uploads`` to allow two-way file sharing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:120
msgid ""
"Your Apache Web server must have ``mod_rewrite`` enabled, and you must "
"have ``trusted_domains`` correctly configured in ``config.php`` to allow "
"external connections (see :doc:`../installation/installation_wizard`). "
"Consider also enabling SSL to encrypt all traffic between your servers ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration_files/federated_cloud_sharing_configuration.rst:125
msgid ""
"Your ownCloud server creates the share link from the URL that you used to"
" log into the server, so make sure that you log into your server using a "
"URL that is accessible to your users. For example, if you log in via its "
"LAN IP address, such as ``http://192.168.10.50``, then your share URL "
"will be something like "
"``http://192.168.10.50/owncloud/index.php/s/jWfCfTVztGlWTJe``, which is "
"not accessible outside of your LAN. This also applies to using the server"
" name; for access outside of your LAN you need to use a fully-qualified "
"domain name such as ``http://myserver.example.com``, rather than "
"``http://myserver``."
msgstr ""

